                <section id="spr-epr" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">2. SPR vs EPR: Selecting Power Range Architecture for Your OEM Charger Product Line</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">PD 3.1's key innovation is splitting power delivery into two distinct ranges:</p>
                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border-t-4 border-brandBlue">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">SPR — Standard Power Range</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-2"><strong>Up to 100W</strong> (20V × 5A)</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-2">Uses the familiar 5V/9V/15V/20V levels from PD 3.0. Fully backward compatible — every PD 3.1 charger supports SPR. Covers phones, tablets, and most ultrabooks.</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs">✅ Standard USB-C cables work (up to 60W)<br>✅ 5A e-marked cables for 65-100W</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border-t-4 border-brandOrange">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandOrange uppercase mb-3">EPR — Extended Power Range</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-2"><strong>100W to 240W</strong> (28V/36V/48V × 5A)</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-2">The new territory unlocked by PD 3.1. Enables laptop charging at full speed, portable monitor power, and emerging use cases like e-bike and power tool charging over USB-C.</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs">⚠️ Requires EPR-rated charger<br>⚠️ Requires EPR-rated cable with EPR e-marker</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-slate-600">The practical takeaway: <strong>SPR handles everything most people need today. EPR is for laptops above 100W and future devices.</strong> If your most power-hungry device is a MacBook Air (30-45W) or iPad Pro (20-30W), you may never use EPR — and that's fine. PD 3.1 chargers work perfectly at SPR levels with standard cables.</p>

